Thanks. Looking at the actual configuration, your management network is:

bond0 = ens1f0 + ens3f1

Mode = 802.3ad (LACP)

VLAN = bond0.100

IP = 10.0.100.210/24

Gateway = 10.0.100.108


And the workload network is:

bond2 = ens1f1 + ens3f0

Mode = active-backup

VLANs = 130, 132, 150


Since you're creating a new worker ISO using:

coreos-installer iso customize

you only need to embed the management network (bond0, ens1f0, ens3f1, and optionally bond0.100) so the node can reach the API server during installation.

bond0.nmconnection

[connection]
id=bond0
type=bond
interface-name=bond0

[bond]
lacp_rate=fast
miimon=100
mode=802.3ad
xmit_hash_policy=layer2+3

[ipv4]
method=disabled

[ipv6]
method=ignore

ens1f0.nmconnection

[connection]
id=ens1f0
type=ethernet
interface-name=ens1f0
master=bond0
slave-type=bond

ens3f1.nmconnection

[connection]
id=ens3f1
type=ethernet
interface-name=ens3f1
master=bond0
slave-type=bond

bond0.100.nmconnection

[connection]
id=bond0.100
type=vlan
interface-name=bond0.100

[vlan]
id=100
parent=bond0

[ipv4]
address1=10.0.100.210/24,10.0.100.108
dns=10.0.100.114;
method=manual

[ipv6]
method=disabled

Then build the worker ISO

Use worker.ign, not master.ign:

coreos-installer iso customize \
  --dest-device /dev/sda \
  --dest-ignition ../ocp-install/worker.ign \
  --network-keyfile bond0.nmconnection \
  --network-keyfile ens1f0.nmconnection \
  --network-keyfile ens3f1.nmconnection \
  --network-keyfile bond0.100.nmconnection \
  -o worker06.iso \
  rhcos-live.x86_64.iso

Important

The IP 10.0.100.210 appears to be the old worker06 address. Confirm that no other node is currently using it:

oc get nodes -o wide

and from another host:

ping 10.0.100.210
arp -an | grep 10.0.100.210

Before generating the ISO, can you confirm:

1. Is 10.0.100.210 the original IP of worker06?


2. Are you using the original worker.ign or extracting a fresh one from the running cluster?



A fresh ignition from the current cluster is preferred.
